# ── Compiled Java class files ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
# WHY: .class files are generated by javac from your .java source files.
#      They are machine-specific binary output — not human-readable source code.
#      Anyone who has Java installed can regenerate them from your .java files,
#      so there is zero reason to store them in version control.
*.class

# ── Java Archive files ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# WHY: .jar files are packaged, compiled Java programs — again, generated output.
#      If someone needs a .jar, they can build it from source.
*.jar

# ── IDE and Editor files ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# WHY: IntelliJ IDEA stores its project config in .idea/ and *.iml files.
#      Eclipse uses .classpath and .project. These are per-developer settings
#      that differ between machines — committing them causes constant conflicts.
.idea/
*.iml
.classpath
.project
.settings/

# ── macOS system files ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# WHY: macOS automatically creates .DS_Store files in every folder you open
#      in Finder. These are invisible to the OS but visible to Git, and they
#      contain nothing useful for your project.
.DS_Store

# ── Windows system files ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Thumbs.db
desktop.ini

# ── Build output directory ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# WHY: If you ever add a build tool or manually compile into an /out or /bin
#      directory, ignore those folders entirely. Only source lives in Git.
out/
bin/

# ── Log files ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# WHY: Log files grow over time and are runtime artifacts, not source code.
*.log
